SECOND REGULAR SESSION
SENATE BILL NO. 1733
103RD GENERA L ASSEMBLY
INTRODUCED BY SENATOR GREGORY (15).
7375S.01I KRISTINA MARTIN, Secretary
AN ACT
To amend chapter 160, RSMo, by adding thereto two new sections relating to school safety.
Be it enacted by the General Assembly of the State of Missouri, as follows:
1 Section A. Chapter 160, RSMo, is amended by adding thereto
2 two new sections, to be known as sections 160.666 and 160.667,
3 to read as follows:
1 160.666. 1. This section and section 160.667 shall be
2 known and may be cited as "Alyssa's Law".
3 2. Beginning with the 2027-28 school year and
4 continuing in all subsequent school years, each local
5 educational agency shall implement a wearable panic alert
6 system at each school facility capable of integrating with
7 local public safety answering point infrastructure to
8 transmit 911 calls or mobile activations.
9 3. In accordance with the emergency operations plan
10 developed under section 160.480, a local educational agency
11 shall provide each staff person with a wearable panic alert
12 device to communicate throughout each school campus that
13 allows for immediate contact with local emergency response
14 agencies.
15 4. The wearable panic alert system shall be capable of
16 initiating a campus-wide emergency notification, such as a
17 lockdown. Notifications shall include automated visual
18 strobes whose colors map to the emergency protocol; an

SB 1733 2
19 automated, direct connection to the intercom or public
20 announcement (PA) infrastructure in place that maps to the
21 emergency protocol; and an automated computer display
22 takeover message that maps to the emergency protocol.
23 5. Upon activation of an alert, the wearable panic
24 alert system shall provide accurate location information at
25 the room and floor level inside the facility and specific
26 areas such as parking lots, playgrounds, athletic fields,
27 and similar areas that are part of the school grounds.
28 6. A local educational agency shall ensure, before the
29 school year begins, all school building personnel receive
30 training on the emergency protocols and appropriate use of
31 the panic alert device described in subsection 3 of this
32 section.
1 160.667. 1. A local educational agency shall ensure,
2 before the school year begins, that emergency response
3 mapping is made available by the provider of the wearable
4 panic alert system required pursuant to section 160.666, at
5 no cost to the local educational agency, to local first
6 responder agencies, in an electronic or digital format, to
7 assist first responders in responding to emergencies at
8 schools. Emergency response maps shall:
9 (1) Be compatible with security software platforms in
10 use by the specific school for which the data is provided
11 without requiring the local law enforcement agencies or
12 school districts to purchase additional software or
13 requiring the integration of third-party software to view
14 the data;
15 (2) Be oriented true north;
16 (3) Be overlaid on school floor plans;
17 (4) Contain site-specific labeling that matches the
18 structure of school buildings, including room labels,

SB 1733 3
19 hallway names, and external door or stairwell numbers and
20 locations of critical utility feeds, emergency equipment
21 such as automated external defibrillators (AEDs), trauma
22 kits, and NARCAN kits;
23 (5) Be capable of creating and managing electronic
24 asset tags that allow the local educational agency to know
25 the unique identifier of the devices such as the serial
26 number, last inspection date, battery replacement date such
27 as battery replacement date for the AED, expiration date
28 such as the NARCAN kit expiration date, and other
29 information pertinent to the appropriate operation of the
30 asset;
31 (6) Have the ability to provide real time updates by
32 building owners with role-based logins to the emergency
33 response maps, where changes are automatically disseminated
34 to emergency responders and 911 mapping applications using
35 existing data in order to ensure the most up-to-date
36 information. Updates shall include changes to the physical
37 structure such as walls, doors, and mobile classrooms, along
38 with changes to the asset tags; and
39 (7) Have ownership retained by the local educational
40 agency with full rights to copy, display, distribute,
41 transmit, and adapt for all lawful purposes, including
42 sharing with government or private entities that are
43 providing or supporting emergency services.
44 2. A local educational agency shall:
45 (1) Ensure all security data, including data from all
46 cameras, maps, and access control within a school building,
47 are accessible by a local law enforcement agency; and
48 (2) Coordinate with a local law enforcement agency to
49 establish appropriate access protocols.

SB 1733 4
50 3. Any records, information, photographs, audio and
51 visual presentations, schematic diagrams, surveys,
52 recommendations, or consultations, or portions thereof,
53 relating directly to the physical security or fire safety of
54 the school facility or revealing security or fire safety
55 systems held by a local educational agency are confidential
56 and exempt from public disclosure under chapter 610.
57 4. Information made confidential and exempt from
58 public disclosure under subsection 3 of this section may be
59 disclosed:
60 (1) To the property owner or local educational
61 agency's leaseholder;
62 (2) In furtherance of the official duties and
63 responsibilities of the agency holding the information;
64 (3) To another local, state, or federal agency in
65 furtherance of that agency's official duties and
66 responsibilities; or
67 (4) Upon a showing of good cause before a court of
68 competent jurisdiction.
69 5. The state board of education may promulgate rules
70 to implement this section as are necessary to protect the
71 health and safety of students and educators. Any rule or
72 portion of a rule, as that term is defined in section
73 536.010, that is created under the authority delegated in
74 this section shall become effective only if it complies with
75 and is subject to all of the provisions of chapter 536 and,
76 if applicable, section 536.028. This section and chapter
77 536 are nonseverable and if any of the powers vested with
78 the general assembly pursuant to chapter 536 to review, to
79 delay the effective date, or to disapprove and annul a rule
80 are subsequently held unconstitutional, then the grant of

SB 1733 5
81 rulemaking authority and any rule proposed or adopted after
82 August 28, 2026, shall be invalid and void.
